title: $A strengthens as commodities rebound
text:
Wed, Jul 29, 2015, 2:23 PM AEST - Australia Markets close in 1 hr 37 mins $A strengthens as commodities rebound AAP â€“ 2 hours 4 minutes ago Recommend Print 
The Australian dollar is firmer after traders took heart from an overnight pause in commodity price declines amid easing concerns about China's sharemarket pull-back. 
At 1200 AEST on Wednesday, the currency was trading at 73.42 US cents, up from 73.15 cents on Tuesday. 
US crude oil prices lifted for the first time in five days, while iron ore rose a further 2.1 per cent while copper and gold also rebounded. 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* 73.42 US cents, from 73.15 cents on Tuesday 
* 90.60 Japanese yen, from 90.40 yen 
* 66.26 euro cents, from 66.17 euro cents 
* 109.43 New Zealand cents, from 109.79 NZ cents 
* 47.03 British pence, from 47.01 pence 
Government bond yields: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.878%, from 1.853%, on Tuesday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.887%, from 2.845% 
* Sept 2015 10-year bond futures contract, at 97.160 (yield 2.840 pct), down from 97.205 (2.795 pct) 
* Sept 2015 3-year bond futures contract, at 98.080 (1.920 pct), down from 98.110 (1.890 per cent) 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session, bond market closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
